<h3>Alkanes</h3>

<h5> AS LEVEL </h5> @* Help users distinguish between Year 12 and Year 13 topics*@


<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Alkanes are saturated hydrocarbons containing only single bonds between carbon atoms. They are part of the homologous series with the general formula <b>C<sub>n</sub>H<sub>2n+2</sub></b>.
</p>

<h2 style="color: red; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">General Formula</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    The general formula for alkanes is <b>C<sub>n</sub>H<sub>2n+2</sub></b>, where <i>n</i> is the number of carbon atoms. This formula applies to all straight-chain and branched alkanes.
</p>

<h2 style="color: red; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Physical Properties</h2>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Boiling Points:</b> Boiling points increase with chain length due to stronger van der Waals forces. Branched alkanes have lower boiling points than straight-chain isomers due to reduced surface area.</li>
    <li><b>Solubility:</b> Alkanes are non-polar and insoluble in water but soluble in organic solvents.</li>
    <li><b>Density:</b> Alkanes are less dense than water.</li>
</ul>

<h2 style="color: red; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Reactivity of Alkanes</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Alkanes are relatively unreactive due to the strong C–C and C–H bonds and the lack of polar functional groups. However, they undergo the following reactions:
</p>
<ol style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li>
        <b>Combustion:</b>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <b>Complete Combustion:</b> Alkanes react with oxygen to produce carbon dioxide and water. Example:
                <code>CH<sub>4</sub> + 2O<sub>2</sub> → CO<sub>2</sub> + 2H<sub>2</sub>O</code>.
            </li>
            <li>
                <b>Incomplete Combustion:</b> In limited oxygen, alkanes produce carbon monoxide or carbon (soot) and water. Example:
                <code>CH<sub>4</sub> + 1.5O<sub>2</sub> → CO + 2H<sub>2</sub>O</code>.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <b>Substitution:</b> Alkanes undergo free radical substitution with halogens (e.g., chlorine or bromine) in the presence of UV light. Example:
        <code>CH<sub>4</sub> + Cl<sub>2</sub> → CH<sub>3</sub>Cl + HCl</code>.
    </li>
</ol>

<h2 style="color: red; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Free Radical Substitution Mechanism</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    The reaction between alkanes and halogens occurs in three steps:
</p>
<ol style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li>
        <b>Initiation:</b> UV light causes homolytic fission of the halogen molecule to form radicals.
        <code>Cl<sub>2</sub> → 2Cl•</code>
    </li>
    <li>
        <b>Propagation:</b> Radicals react with the alkane to form new radicals and products.
        <ul>
            <li><code>CH<sub>4</sub> + Cl• → CH<sub>3</sub>• + HCl</code></li>
            <li><code>CH<sub>3</sub>• + Cl<sub>2</sub> → CH<sub>3</sub>Cl + Cl•</code></li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <b>Termination:</b> Radicals combine to form stable molecules.
        <ul>
            <li><code>CH<sub>3</sub>• + Cl• → CH<sub>3</sub>Cl</code></li>
            <li><code>Cl• + Cl• → Cl<sub>2</sub></code></li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ol>

<h2 style="color: red; font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">Isomerism in Alkanes</h2>
<p style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    Alkanes exhibit structural isomerism:
</p>
<ul style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;">
    <li><b>Chain Isomerism:</b> Different arrangements of the carbon chain. Example: Butane (C<sub>4</sub>H<sub>10</sub>) has two isomers: n-butane and 2-methylpropane.</li>
</ul>

